                            <layoutDesc><layout>
                                    <p>The tablet is inscribed on <rs type="sides" key="opisthographic">both sides</rs>. It preserves only one inscription on side A (15A) and three on side B (16B, <ref target="i-dodone-online-17b">17B</ref>, and 18B). Inscriptions 15A and 16B were written by the same hand: 15A records Thelytos’ question, while 16B gives his name. Evangelidis edited <ref target="i-dodone-online-17b">17B</ref> together with 16B, and <ref target="i-dodone-online-17b">17B</ref> is likewise included under the same lemma in <bibl><ptr target="#CIOD"/></bibl>. However, as the editors of <bibl><ptr target="#IDodoneDVC"/></bibl> point out, both <ref target="i-dodone-online-17b">17B</ref> and 18B are independent inscriptions. Inscription 18B was not identified by Evangelidis. </p>
                                    <p n="Dialect"><rs type="dialect" ref="#Doric">Doric</rs></p>
                                    <p n="Alphabet"><rs type="alphabet" ref="#Archaic">Archaic (Corinthian)</rs>.</p>
                            </layout></layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                        <handNote>
                            <p>Letter height: ca. 0.3 cm. Interlinear space: ca. 0.25 cm. The inscription is executed in regular lettering with a carefully planned layout. The three lines observe word division consistently, and a vacant space is intentionally left at the right end of the tablet.</p>
                        </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
